			</td><td width="2%">&nbsp;</td><td width="44%"> Abstract
			<div style="text-align:justify;">
				<P>
					<B>Introduction</B>: It is known that from the 90s of the 20th century, which is considered to be the decade of the brain, both philosophers and cognitive scientists have profoundly studied the human mind. In this context, the ideas of Jerry Fodor, who had been theorized hypothetically since the 70s from existing theories, contributed to interdisciplinary continuation inherent in Cognitive Science. This research captures the mind-brain problem which is far from biological or philosophical consensus, and supports epistemological for deepening these investigations today provides justification for our research was justified in that it captures the mind-brain problem that is far from a biological or philosophical setting, and offers epistemological support for deepening these investigations now a days. Such as global cognitive processes.
					<B>Objectives</B>: Ascertain the hypothesis of possible relationships between the philosophical functionalism and the nature of research, including biological, raised by the Cognitive Science; - structure the points in which the philosophical functionalism proposed by Fodor may help to understanding of the functioning of mind-brain relationship; - identify evidence of neurobiological values that Cognitive Science benefited from the philosophical functionalism.					<B>Methods</B>: This project is theoretical in nature and, because of that, its methodology had been made by reading philosophy texts, based on the relationship between philosophy of mind and cognitive science. Discussions, corrections and suggestions by the evaluators themselves were added to the readings at the reading times. At first, I was made a literature mapping and exposure of the material gathered to run the project, as well as a possibility for future research.					<B>Results</B>: After reviewing the literature, especially the work of Jerry Fodor, philosopher and cognition scientist, and neuroscientific data collection, we found an innovative potential of research involving quantum computing to the phenomena of cognitive functioning of the human brain. Even if the initial project provided for the interdisciplinary relationship we see here, a factor that makes changing strategy and the involvement of other areas of knowledge for this research in its initial, impractical proposal. However, we understand that this filter momentary limiter present in an invigorating way for future research.					<B>Conclusion</B>: Fodor called the encapsulated functional mental processes by vertical. However, through his research, Fodor realized that not all mental processes were capable of vertical integration. Some cognitive processing were global, in an holistic approach. In other words, it was of horizontal processes. A central processor without brain position. 
It follows, then, that the fodorian problem can be sustained and avail themselves of further research. Based on the interdisciplinary basic neuroscience studies without losing, of course, the philosophical bias. And that this search path would include a new approach regarding the own mental representation and holistic approach to cognition. The fact that the problem is still open indicates new research possibilities that could use the current investigation in this research.
				</P>
